         Extracted from NZ PC World magazine, December 1999, page 120


@1
1.@5 Altair 8800: The machine that inspired a generation.

@1
2.@5 Apple II: The definitive PC - at least until IBM joined the party.

@1
3.@5 IBM PC AT: Set standards still in use today.

@1
4.@5 Compaq Deskpro 386: Pioneered a new Intel processor before IBM did, 
   inspiring a horde of other clone vendors.

@1
5:@5 Radio Shack TRS-80: The first successful notebook.

@1
6:@5 Apple Macintosh 512K: The first truly useful Mac.

@1
7:#8 Amiga@5: Did multimedia tricks in 1985 that today's PCs still can't do.

@1
8:@5 Commodore 64: Possibly the most beloved computer of all time.

@1
9:@5 IBM ThinkPad 560: Thin, light and durable: our pick for the perfect travelling 
   companion.

@1
10:@5 Palm Pilot: Small is beautiful.
